# [EODIR](../wg/eodir.html)

## Summary

The Education and Outreach Directorate (EODIR) met at IETF 126 to discuss various community outreach programs, diversity initiatives, newcomer mentoring, and specialized training programs. Key updates were provided on regional talent programs, the Hands-on GitHub tutorial, the Working Group Chairs Forum, the SISTERS program, and the Guides program.

---

## Key Discussion Points

### 1. EODIR Outreach & Regional Initiatives
* **Outreach Wiki & IETF 128 Planning:** Dhruv Dhody (on behalf of Yaroslav) provided an update on EODIR outreach activities. Greg Wood shared the link to the [EODIR Outreach Wiki](https://wiki.ietf.org/en/group/eodir/outreach). Dhruv Dhody encouraged the community to begin planning regional outreach activities early for the upcoming IETF 128 meeting in Kuala Lumpur (KL).
* **IIESO Connection Program:** Mohit P. Tahiliani presented on the India Internet Engineering Society’s "Connections" event—a pre-IETF meetup designed to educate local participants and encourage remote/in-person attendance. The eighth edition on July 11 gathered 40–45 in-person attendees. Featured topics included PQC, AI native networking, eBPF, and queue management. Mohit P. Tahiliani also announced an upcoming "RFCs we love" session at APNIC 62 in India in September.
* **Chinese Youth Talent Program:** Chunli Lay updated the group on the Chinese Youth Talent Program. Due to budget constraints, the program sponsored 15 students for this meeting (compared to 60 at IETF 125 in Shenzhen). Demographics show 63% are PhD candidates and 20% are Master's candidates. To date, participants have submitted over 30 individual drafts and delivered more than 10 working group/research group presentations. Georgios Karagiannis shared the [Chinese Youth Talent Program Report Link](https://wiki.ietf.org/en/group/eodir/chinese-youth-talent-program) in the chat.
* **The IO Foundation (TIOF) Fellowship:** Jean F. Queralt reported on the remote fellowship program for IETF 126, which received 22 submissions across APAC and Africa. Eleven fellows from Indonesia and Pakistan actively participated remotely. The program focused on mandatory sessions (New Participants Program, HotRFC, Plenary, IRTF Open) and remote check-ins. In response to a chat question from Benson Muite regarding African participation, Jean F. Queralt clarified that while one African participant was accepted, they did not continue participation past the preparation phase.

### 2. Hands-on GitHub Tutorial
* Mirja Kühlewind and Karen O'Donoghue reviewed the Sunday session: "[Hands-on tutorial: Using the Github web interface for authoring Internet-Drafts](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-eodir-sessc-hands-on-tutorial-using-the-github-web-interface-for-authoring-internet-drafts-00)".
* The session was limited to 30 registrants (about 31–32 attended) to ensure hands-on assistance, which was supported by Kevin Kelly.
* **Feedback & Suggestions:**
  * Jean Mahoney recommended introducing GitHub Actions earlier, using dummy markdown documents, and commenting out template features so that initial automated tests pass on the first commit. She also suggested a classroom layout that allows instructors to walk around more easily.
  * In response to a chat query from Tara Tarakiyee about online versions, Mirja Kühlewind noted that while recording the interactive session is difficult, a smaller online interactive session (10–15 people) could be considered.
  * Benson Muite suggested referencing the [Carpentries Incubator GitHub guide](https://carpentries-incubator.github.io/github-without-command-line/) as a potential resource.
  * Mohit P. Tahiliani suggested creating a short, pre-recorded 20-minute YouTube tutorial showing screen shares of the process so participants can prepare before attending the live hands-on session.

### 3. Working Group Chairs Forum
* Karen O'Donoghue reported on the Working Group Chairs Forum. She noted that discussions are underway with Area Director Roman Danyliw to restructure the forum's scheduling to resolve Meetecho conflicts.
* Rich Salz highlighted a tool demonstration by Mark Nottingham showing how Working Group information and draft data can be integrated into an LLM for querying. This was well received and kept technical discussions focused on tooling rather than broader AI policy questions.

### 4. Diversity and Inclusivity Initiatives
* **SISTERS Program:** The Sisters representative reported highly successful networking sessions, including a breakfast on Monday and a heavily attended lunch on Tuesday. The Sisters' Co-Chair noted that the Sisters' charter (which ran through IETF 124) is being updated on the mailing list to remove its hard expiration date.
* **New Participants Program:** Michelle Cotton reported that approximately 42% of first-to-fifth-time attendees participated either on-site or remotely. Feedback indicates that newcomers feel welcomed and some are quickly transitioning into draft authors. To assist remote presenters, Michelle Cotton proposed adding an extra MeetEcho test session on Saturdays prior to the meeting week.
* **Guides Program:** Wes Hardaker reported 22 matches made 3 to 4 weeks prior to the meeting. Two matches were remote, and one remote participant remained unmatched. The addition of the "always willing to help" flag in the backend database has improved matching, though guides need to be reminded to keep their active working group profiles updated. Jay Daley noted that three new ICANN board members attended the newcomer training and highly praised the program's structure.

### 5. Any Other Business (AOB)
* Kaliya Young shared a link to research completed with the support of the Summer of Protocols (now the Protocol Institute): [IETF Research Link](https://identitywoman.net/ietf-research/). She noted she would share the details on the EODIR mailing list.
* Greg Wood introduced Akanksha Gupta, the new Research and Insights Analyst at the IETF LLC, who is currently analyzing community surveys and feedback.

